This would imply a decrease of 10% in 3 days. This is not unreasonable, Facebook's stock did this multiple times in March. Also, there is a tendency of the market to overreact to fundamental news. The price was only $234.50 on the close the day before. Thus we increase this value from the theoretical base rate to 2%.

I guess markets will have a losing week before resolution of this question with abundant reasons, the latest of which is tropical storm "Isaias", which could strengthen again and organize into a hurricane, and now threatens to affect the entire East coast of the USA. Although the facebook stock has de-coupled from Nasdaq 100 and has thus become an alpha trade over the last few days, earnings and news tend to be traded on only as long as they are rumors, and tend to stop doing so when they're facts. I struggle to interpret the news on tiktok with regards to facebook's future, but when you look at it closely, the risk of espionage on personal data (especially when they get lost by the company) is not so much different from the one in facebook's data pile, so recommendations of the pentagon may also apply to facebook and their lax data handling. Combining this with the repeated congressional hearings, it seems to me that "nationalizing the data stock" could to be a target of national security authorities in the US with the "National Security interest" as a reason, in which a significantly lower prize and finally a buy-out could be the result. facebook already acts like a governmental body in times (e.g. supporting "predicitve policing"), so why not be a national agency openly in the future? To me it seems, the process has already started in 2020.

My forecast is based on options price data. I saw how others used option prices in their forecasts and wanted to suggest an improvement on that method. The price of a call spread divided by the difference in strikes is roughly equal to the probability that the call spread expires in the money. (Think about the limiting case as the difference in strikes goes to 0 to see why—in this limit it is exactly true). This can be used to back out a market-implied CDF for the stock price at expiration. I used option prices in the Aug 7 weekly expiration to find these values using the closest available strikes. I used the call spreads with boundaries at the relevant stock prices, and took the average of the two implied probabilities to back out what the implied probability would be very roughly for a call spread centered on the relevant value.
